  <p>Carbon neutral cleaning is not a label applied to standard cleaning operations with a carbon offset added at the end. It requires three integrated activities. measuring emissions, reducing them at source, and verifying remaining offsets. with documented evidence at every step suitable for procurement and ESG audit.</p>

  <h2>What Carbon Neutral Cleaning Involves</h2>
  <p>
    Carbon neutral cleaning requires three distinct activities: measurement of direct and indirect greenhouse gas emissions from cleaning operations, reduction of emissions at source through equipment selection, product choices and operational practices, and verified offsetting of remaining emissions through accredited carbon offset programs. Documentation of all three activities must be maintained and made available for ESG and procurement reporting.
  </p>
  <p>
    Emissions sources in commercial cleaning include vehicle fleet emissions from service delivery travel, energy consumption by cleaning equipment, chemical manufacturing and transport upstream impacts, and waste generated by cleaning consumables.
  </p>

  <CalloutBox heading="What this means for ESG and procurement teams">
    <p>When evaluating carbon neutral claims from cleaning providers, ask specifically for the emissions measurement methodology, the accreditation framework applied (carbon neutral or equivalent), evidence of documented reduction initiatives, and offset certificate verification records. A "carbon neutral" claim without these four elements is a marketing assertion. not a verified status.</p>
  </CalloutBox>

  <h2>Where Carbon Neutral Status Applies</h2>
  <p>
    Carbon neutral cleaning is relevant across all sectors CPC serves:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Government procurement frameworks increasingly require emissions reporting from suppliers</li>
    <li>Corporate clients with net-zero commitments require verified Scope 3 supply chain data from cleaning providers</li>
    <li>Green Star building certifications may impose environmental reporting obligations on cleaning contractors</li>
    <li>ESG reporting programs require supplier-level emissions data for Scope 3 calculation</li>
  </ul>

